<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-970-672  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 970 672.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lan Times  Nov 1989 v6 n11 p82(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>David and Goliath. (microcomputer-based LANs coexisting withrather than replacing minicomputer and mainframe hosts) (includesrelated articles on the dangers of not migrating to LANs and on asurvey on LAN migration)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hurwicz, Mike.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many computer industry experts predict the imminent demise ofmainframe and minicomputer host-based systems asmicrocomputer-based LANs continue to proliferate in large andsmall organizations.andP;  LANs are the best choice for many importantbusiness computing applications, but there are still many jobs bigiron does better than networked micros.andP;  LANs let users share dataand expensive resources while retaining the personal control andperformance of microcomputers, improving microcomputer securityand performance as well.andP;  However, the overhead of transferringdata around a network often makes use of a host, which has lessinternal wiring, a better choice for an application.andP;  Sometimes alarge host is retained because EDP managers do not want the botherand expense of a complicated conversion.andP;  The relative strengthsand weaknesses of LANs and host-based systems are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksMainframe ComputersMinicomputersHardware SelectionUser NeedsMISComparisonManagement of EDPOrganizational Behavior.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>